kubernetes/kubernetes#135349.body:
### What would you like to be added?

In https://grep.app/search?q=runtime.ErrorHandlers one can see that some downstreams adapted to the [API change in 1.31](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/commit/5a130d2b71e5d70cfff15087f4d521c6b68fb01e) by simply ignoring all the new parameters (message string, key/value pairs) and only using the error, like they did before. Apparently someone took the path of least resistance when updating their Kubernetes dependencies, without looking at the upstream change.

Some examples:

https://github.com/microsoft/retina/blob/a58597a120051a91f673729c0e149ba0942ca939/pkg/k8s/watcher_linux.go#L43-L52

https://github.com/upbound/xgql/blob/070bbbf7ef87de93f4376d73413ac7ad4c46b607/cmd/xgql/main.go#L202-L206

#### Problem and solution

Not only is this capturing the problem incompletely, it will also **crash for those HandleErrorWithContext/Logger calls which pass a nil error**. Consumers can use the helper from https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/135419 to produce a single error with all information.

Finding all broken usages and notifying the owners is problematic because there seem to be too many and manually checking all search results is error-prone. Not all consumers are visible on GitHub.

##### Alternative proposal (rejected!): let's break the API once more in 1.36 and change the parameters of `ErrorHandler`.

```Go
// ErrorHandler is the callback invoked by all HandleError functions.
type ErrorHandler func(ctx context.Context, errLog ErrLog)

// ErrLog capture all parameters necessary for producing an error log with structured logging.
type ErrLog struct {
    // Err is a Go error which was passed up to the code which called HandleError. May be nil.
    Err error

    // Message is a (usually) fixed string describing the problem.
    Msg string

    // KVs contains key/value pairs with varying additional information which can be
    // passed to e.g. klog, logr, or slog.
    KVs []any
}

// AsError returns an error where the Error implementation
// formats the ErrLog using klog text format, without any headers.
// The returned error also wraps the underlying error, if there is one.
//
// If you need a string, use AsError().Error().
func (el ErrLog) AsError() error {
    ...
}
```

Breaking the API is intentional. It notifies all consumers that they have to double-check their implementation. Adding the AsError method simplifies the life of those consumers which only know how to deal with an error.

@tnthornton @ritwikranjan: what do you think about this proposal? Sorry for calling your out here, but I want feedback from someone who handled the previous API change incorrectly.

### Why is this needed?

We want to convert more code to use `HandleErrorWithLogger/Context` and as part of that often remove creating an error when there is none to begin with.

Pending examples:

- https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/134806/files
- https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/134806/files

Already merged (potentially incomplete list):
- https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/134102
- https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/134450

We need to pause making such changes until this issue is resolved because even if downstream didn't properly implement `ErrorHandler`, we don't want to turn that into a real problem for them.

/cc @mayank-agrwl @deads2k

/wg structured-logging
/sig instrumentation
/sig api-machinery

